te bridge over water with a mountain backdrop”** by David Vives | **4 Feb 2026** | Illuminated Golden Gate Bridge against a dramatic sunset | Located/tagged at Golden Gate Bridge, San Francisco. ([unsplash.com](https://unsplash.com/photos/golden-gate-bridge-over-water-with-a-mountain-backdrop-K4097es3zcA?utm_source=openai)) |\n| **Unsplash – “The golden gate bridge spans across the water”** by Logan Easterling | **21 Feb 2026** | Golden Gate Bridge at sunset as seen from the water | More urban/scenic view; published in 2026. ([unsplash.com](https://unsplash.com/photos/the-golden-gate-bridge-spans-across-the-water-67Sfnfo50SI?utm_source=openai)) |\n\n**Caution:** these are *recently published* pages; the publication date does not always guarantee the photo was captured on that exact date.\n\n## Supporting text sources\n\n| Source | Why it’s useful |\n|---|---|\n| **Golden Gate Bridge official site** | Good for accurate bridge description: the bridge draws more than **10 million visitors** annually and is known for its **746-foot towers**, main cables, **International Orange** color, and Art Deco styling. ([goldengate.org](https://www.goldengate.org/?utm_source=openai)) |\n| **Golden Gate National Recreation Area – National Park Service** | Context for the landscape around the bridge: the recreation area spans about **80,000 acres**, includes sites north and south of the bridge, more than **130 miles of trails**, and many historic structures. ([nps.gov](https://www.nps.gov/goga/planyourvisit/placestogo.htm?utm_source=openai)) |\n| **Parks Conservancy – Golden Gate Bridge** | Concise interpretive copy: the bridge opened in **1937**, is a **1.7-mile suspension span** between San Francisco and Marin, and is framed by Golden Gate national parklands. ([parksconservancy.org](https://www.parksconservancy.org/parks/golden-gate-bridge?utm_source=openai)) |\n| **Parks Conservancy – sunset spots** | Useful for sunset-angle/location copy: **Marshall’s Beach**, tucked between Baker Beach and the Golden Gate Bridge, is described as offering unique perspectives on the commonly photographed landscape. ([parksconservancy.org](https://www.parksconservancy.org/park-e-ventures-article/jaw-dropping-sunset-spots-our-parks?utm_source=openai)) |\n| **Recent local context – SF Chronicle / SFGate** | If you want timely copy, San Francisco has planned a rare **July 4, 2026** fireworks display launched from/near the Golden Gate Bridge, with suggested viewing areas including Crissy Field, Marina Green, and the northern Embarcadero. ([sfchronicle.com](https://www.sfchronicle.com/sf/article/july-fourth-fireworks-golden-gate-bridge-22306092.php?utm_source=openai)) |\n\n## Suggested caption / supporting copy\n\n**Short caption:**  \n*The Golden Gate Bridge glows at sunset, its International Orange towers cutting through fog and evening light above San Francisco Bay.*\n\n**Longer supporting text:**  \n*Opened in 1937, the Golden Gate Bridge remains one of San Francisco’s most recognizable landmarks: a 1.7-mile suspension span linking the city with Marin County. At sunset, its International Orange color, Art Deco towers, and sweeping cables are framed by the surrounding national parklands, beaches, fog, and bay views—making locations such as Marshall’s Beach, Baker Beach, Crissy Field, and the Marin Headlands especially popular for photography.* ([goldengate.org](https://www.goldengate.org/?utm_source=openai))"},"sequence_number":447}

